To trigger validation even if fields are not touched, you can use the `trigger` method provided by React Hook Form on form submission. This method manually triggers the validation for one or more fields.

Here's an updated example code snippet that uses `handleSubmit` to trigger `trigger` validation on form submission:

```
import { useForm } from "react-hook-form";

function App() {
  const { register, handleSubmit, formState: { errors }, trigger } = useForm();
  const onSubmit = data => console.log(data);

  const submitForm = async () => {
    try {
      await trigger(); // trigger validation
      handleSubmit(onSubmit)(); // submit form if inputs are valid
    } catch (err) {
      console.log(err);
    }
  };

  return (
    <form onSubmit={submitForm}>
      <div>
        <label>First Name</label>
        <input {...register("firstName", { required: true })} />
        {errors.firstName && <span>This field is required</span>}
      </div>
      <div>
        <label>Last Name</label>
        <input {...register("lastName", { required: true })} />
        {errors.lastName && <span>This field is required</span>}
      </div>
      <button type="submit">Submit</button>
    </form>
  );
}
```

By calling `trigger` before `handleSubmit`, the validation will be triggered even if the form inputs are not touched. If the inputs are valid, `handleSubmit` will be called to submit the form and execute the `onSubmit` function. If there are errors, `trigger` will throw an error and you can handle it accordingly.

