    } catch (error) {
      console.error("An error occurred while fetching configuration data", error);
    }
  };

  if (!isPreConfigured) {
    fetchData();
  }
}, [isPreConfigured, baseUrl, httpClient, setConfigurationData, setWhatsAppEnabled, setwhatsAppInboundEnabled, enableSms]);
```

Improvements:
- The code now includes error handling using try-catch statements to catch any errors that occur during the API request and handling them accordingly.
- The fetchData function is now only executed if isPreConfigured is false, reducing potential redundant requests.
- The useEffect dependencies include all variables and functions that are used in the function, ensuring that the function is re-executed when these values change.
- The setConfigurationData function now uses the previous state as a parameter to ensure that previous state values are not lost when updating the state.

The code is executed twice because the useEffect hook is running both on initial render and on every update. In the code, it is passing an empty dependency array as the second argument to useEffect. This means that the effect function will run after the first render and never again unless a dependency updates. 

However, it seems that the condition outside the fetchData function is not a dependency of useEffect, so when the condition changes, the component state is updated, which triggers a re-render, and the useEffect hook gets executed again. Since the condition is now true, fetchData function is called again, and the code gets executed once more.

To fix this issue, you could include the condition as a dependency of the useEffect hook. However, since the condition is also used in the fetchData function, it should be declared as a variable inside the effect function scope, like this:

```
useEffect(() => {
  let isMounted = true;
  const fetchData = async () => {
    if (isMounted && !isPreConfigured) {
      try {
        const response = await httpClient.get("api/1/configure/data");
        const configurationData = response.data;

        setConfigurationData((prevData) => ({
          ...prevData,
          [baseUrl]: configurationData.baseUrl,
        }));
        setWhatsAppEnabled(configurationData.whatsAppConfig.enabled ?? false);
        setwhatsAppInboundEnabled(
          configurationData.whatsAppConfig.inboundEnabled ?? false
        );
        enableSms(configurationData.smsConfig.enabled ?? false);
      } catch (error) {
        console.error("An error occurred while fetching configuration data", error);
      }
    }
  };

  fetchData();

  return () => {
    isMounted = false;
  };
}, [isPreConfigured, baseUrl, httpClient, setConfigurationData, setWhatsAppEnabled, setwhatsAppInboundEnabled, enableSms]);
```

By using a variable isMounted within the effect function, it ensures that if the component unmounts before the fetchData function completes, the subsequent calls to setState will not trigger a state update on an unmounted component.

