You've created a new folder in your Firebase storage and uploaded an image there, which is a good start. And when you set the `image` field of your `PastMK` document to a string like `"PastMK/some.png"`, you're telling your app to look in the `PastMK` folder in Firebase storage for the `some.png` image.

However, you also need to make sure that the security rules for your Firebase storage allow anyone to read from the `PastMK` folder. You can do this by adding a new rule to your storage security rules, like this:

```
service firebase.storage {
  match /b/{bucket}/o {
    // ...

    // Allow anyone to read from the PastMK folder
    match /PastMK/{allPaths=**} {
      allow read;
    }
  }
}
```

This rule allows anyone to read any file in the `PastMK` folder. Make sure to update the bucket name (`{bucket}`) to the name of your Firebase storage bucket.

Once you've updated your storage rules, make sure to publish the changes to ensure that they take effect. Then try reloading your app to see if the image displays correctly.

